   =20
      Exit vs. voice
   =20
 =20

Some companies have good managers and other companies have bad managers. If=
 you are an investor, one thing that you can do is buy stock in companies w=
ith good managers and avoid buying stock in companies with bad managers.
  [2]
 Another thing that you can do is buy stock in companies with bad managers =
and then run an activist campaign to replace them with good managers, reapi=
ng a big profit if it works, but that is kind of an advanced move and the a=
verage retail investor or even mutual fund can=E2=80=99t really do it.
A third thing that you can do is buy stock in companies with bad managers a=
nd then vote against management on advisory nonbinding shareholder proposal=
s to register your disapproval. This is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0distinctly third-bes=
t? You won=E2=80=99t accomplish much. US shareholder democracy is weird: Sh=
areholders get to vote on stuff, but their votes are mostly symbolic. There=
 is   some mechanism that leads from =E2=80=9Cthe shareholders don=E2=80=99=
t like the managers and keep voting against=C2=A0them on symbolic things=E2=
=80=9D to =E2=80=9Can activist shareholder gets the votes to=C2=A0fire the =
managers and replace them with someone else,=E2=80=9D but it is not straigh=
tforward or quick. And for the most part it would be insane to buy shares i=
n a company you hate and just vote your shares against the managers at the =
annual meeting. You=E2=80=99d accomplish nothing, and you=E2=80=99d still o=
wn shares in a company you hate.
On the other hand, if you=E2=80=99re an index fund, that=E2=80=99s kind of =
the whole business. Here=E2=80=99s a fun paper by Joseph Farizo, forthcomin=
g in the Journal of Corporate Finance, titled =E2=80=9C(Black)Rock the Vote=
: Index Funds and Opposition to Management=E2=80=9D:
I show index funds are more likely to oppose management on contentious mana=
gement sponsored proposals at firms held only by their family=E2=80=99s ind=
ex funds than on proposals at firms co-held by their family=E2=80=99s activ=
e funds. Additionally, shareholder proposals garner a greater level of supp=
ort by index funds when the firm=E2=80=99s shares are not simultaneously he=
ld by a fund=E2=80=99s same-family active funds. Consistent with =E2=80=9Cl=
ocked-in=E2=80=9D motives to monitor, these results imply index funds parti=
cipate as more engaged voters when same-family active funds avoid holding p=
ositions in a firm.
I think the intuition here is something like: If you run a big asset manage=
ment=C2=A0firm with lots of mutual funds, there will be some companies that=
 you like and some companies that you don=E2=80=99t like.
  [3]
=C2=A0In your actively managed funds, you will buy the companies that you l=
ike and avoid the companies that you don=E2=80=99t like. In your passively =
managed index funds, you will buy the companies that you like and=C2=A0also=
=C2=A0the companies that you don=E2=80=99t like. But you will =E2=80=94 mos=
tly=C2=A0symbolically =E2=80=94=C2=A0vote against the managers at the compa=
nies you don=E2=80=99t like, because you don=E2=80=99t like them.

