   =20
      ESG vs. Anti-ESG
   =20
 =20

If you are an investment manager, and you believe that climate change is re=
al and bad and caused by fossil fuels, one thing that you might do is avoid=
 investing in fossil-fuel companies. Here are two ways you might explain th=
at choice, to yourself or your clients or anyone else who asks:
=09I think fossil-fuel companies are bad for the world, so I do not want to=
 fund them. This=C2=A0will raise the cost of capital of fossil-fuel extract=
ion, which will lead to less fossil-fuel extraction and less climate change=
.=09I think that climate change is real and caused by fossil fuels, and I t=
hink that the world will increasingly realize that, and consumers and regul=
ators will respond by, for instance, taxing or banning fossil-fuel extracti=
on, or shifting away from gasoline-powered cars, or whatever. So fossil-fue=
l companies have a lot of risk of falling demand or onerous regulation, and=
 the market underprices that risk.

Those two views might lead to different investment decisions. Approach 1 mi=
ght tell you to avoid investing in a big oil company that also does a lot o=
f innovative renewable-energy work, because you think it is morally bad, ev=
en though you think it is financially=C2=A0well positioned for a climate tr=
ansition. Approach 2 might tell you to avoid investing in a hotel company w=
ith lots of beachfront properties, because it is at risk from climate chang=
e, even though it did nothing wrong. But there are a lot of simple overlapp=
ing cases. Pure-play thermal coal companies might be out under either appro=
ach.
Both of these approaches can be loosely described as =E2=80=9CESG,=E2=80=9D=
 environmental, social and governance investing. Technically they are=C2=A0=
 both =E2=80=9CE,=E2=80=9D but you could have analogous approaches for soci=
al and governance issues: Are these things=C2=A0goals=C2=A0that you want to=
 achieve alongside your financial goals, or are they=C2=A0risk factors=C2=
=A0that affect your financial analysis?=C2=A0Purists might say that only Ap=
proach 2 is ESG=C2=A0investing, that ESG investing is about considering env=
ironmental, social and governance risks in making financial decisions, whil=
e Approach 1 is something else (=E2=80=9Csocially responsible investing=E2=
=80=9D).
But most discussions of ESG are not done by purists, and much of the time t=
here is no need to draw this distinction. Either approach excludes coal com=
panies, fine. If you are a big asset manager, you can tell people that you =
are focused on ESG issues to improve returns, and you can tell people that =
you are addressing major global problems through your ESG investing, and no=
body worries much that those two things are different.
  [4]

Meanwhile in US Republican Party politics there is a big anti-ESG movement =
now. Here, too, though, the confusion of the two ESG approaches is =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0confusing. Here is  DealBook today:

Gov. Ron DeSantis of Florida yesterday advanced his campaign against enviro=
nmental, social and governance investing. The State Board of Administration=
, on which he sits,  adopted his proposal to ban the consideration of =E2=
=80=9Csocial, political or ideological interests=E2=80=9D when making inves=
tment decisions for the state=E2=80=99s pension fund.
=E2=80=9CCorporate power has increasingly been utilized to impose an ideolo=
gical agenda on the American people through the perversion of financial inv=
estment priorities under the euphemistic banners of environmental, social a=
nd corporate governance and diversity, inclusion and equity,=E2=80=9D DeSan=
tis, a Republican,  said in a statement.
The resolution imposes broad limits on the pension fund=E2=80=99s investmen=
ts. State administrators will be instructed to prioritize =E2=80=9Cthe high=
est return on investment for beneficiaries, without consideration for nonpe=
cuniary beliefs or political factors.=E2=80=9D

You can read  the resolution here; it objects to ESG =E2=80=9Cprinciples,=
=E2=80=9D and says:

The evaluation by the Board of an investment decision must be based only on=
 pecuniary factors. As used in this section, =E2=80=9Cpecuniary factor=E2=
=80=9D means a factor that the board prudently determines is expected to ha=
ve a material effect on the risk and return of an investment based on appro=
priate investment horizons consistent with the fund=E2=80=99s investment ob=
jectives and funding policy. Pecuniary factors do not include the considera=
tion of the furtherance of social, political, or ideological interests.
The board may not subordinate the interests of the participants and benefic=
iaries to other objectives and may not sacrifice investment return or take =
on additional investment risk to promote any non-pecuniary factors. The wei=
ght given to any pecuniary factor by the board should appropriately reflect=
 a prudent assessment of its impact on risk and returns.

Well. If you are an ESG purist, you will say that there are no such things =
as =E2=80=9CESG principles.=E2=80=9D There are ESG=C2=A0risk factors. The p=
rinciple=C2=A0of Approach-2, ESG-purist investing is =E2=80=9Cmake as much =
money as possible, by considering environmental, social and governance risk=
 factors in your investment decisions.=E2=80=9D The only things that ESG pu=
rist investors consider are =E2=80=9Cpecuniary factors,=E2=80=9D and they w=
eigh them based on their prudent assessments of their impact on risk and re=
turns over appropriate investment horizons.=C2=A0 It=E2=80=99s just that th=
ey think that climate transition risk is a big pecuniary factor. We   talke=
d the other day about a sustainable-finance professor who wants to rebrand =
ESG investing as =E2=80=9Cmaterial risk factors,=E2=80=9D which is a very E=
SG-purist way of putting it.
Or here is  the letter that Larry Fink, the chief executive officer of Blac=
kRock Inc., sent to corporate CEOs in 2020. =E2=80=9CA Fundamental Reshapin=
g of Finance,=E2=80=9D is the headline, and it says things like =E2=80=9CEv=
ery government, company, and shareholder must confront climate change=E2=80=
=9D and =E2=80=9CBlackRock announced a number of initiatives to place susta=
inability at the center of our investment approach.=E2=80=9D It is perhaps =
the high water mark of robust ESG rhetoric from asset managers; since then,=
 Republican opposition has gotten bolder and Fink has gotten more timid. (H=
is  letter this year says things like =E2=80=9CWe focus on sustainability n=
ot because we=E2=80=99re environmentalists, but because we are capitalists =
and fiduciaries to our clients,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CStakeholder capitalis=
m is not about politics. It is not a social or ideological agenda. It is no=
t =E2=80=98woke.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D) But even that 2020 letter=C2=A0is reall=
y about financial risk and long-term profitability:

Because capital markets pull future risk forward, we will see changes in ca=
pital allocation more quickly than we see changes to the climate itself. In=
 the near future =E2=80=93 and sooner than most anticipate =E2=80=93 there =
will be a significant reallocation of capital.
As a fiduciary, our responsibility is to help clients navigate this transit=
ion. Our investment conviction is that sustainability- and climate-integrat=
ed portfolios can provide better risk-adjusted returns to investors. And wi=
th the impact of sustainability on investment returns increasing, we believ=
e that sustainable investing is the strongest foundation for client portfol=
ios going forward.

Just pecuniary factors.
But I suspect that Ron DeSantis suspects that lots of ESG investors are=C2=
=A0not=C2=A0purists, that they have hybrid motives, that they are not=C2=A0=
only=C2=A0concerned with financial risk but also have substantive environme=
ntal and social goals. And so he confuses the issue too.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CGove=
rnor Ron DeSantis Eliminates ESG Considerations from State Pension Investme=
nts,=E2=80=9D is the headline on his  press release. Did he? Is that what h=
appened? If you are an investment manager for Florida and you are convinced=
 that climate change is a material risk factor for some companies, can=E2=
=80=99t you still consider that risk? As a pecuniary factor, not an ideolog=
ical one?
A certain amount of the ESG fight will take the form of broad public statem=
ents of principles. BlackRock will say =E2=80=9Cwe need a fundamental resha=
ping of finance that puts sustainability at the center,=E2=80=9D and Republ=
icans will say =E2=80=9Cwe need to crack down on woke capital,=E2=80=9D and=
 BlackRock will say =E2=80=9Cdid we say fundamental reshaping of finance, w=
hoops, no, we just meant fiduciary consideration of material risk factors.=
=E2=80=9D But a lot of it will take the form (and has  already taken the fo=
rm) of fact-intensive debates about particular investment decisions. Some i=
nvestment manager will say =E2=80=9Cwe are underweight oil and gas companie=
s because we are concerned about the financial impact of climate transition=
 risk,=E2=80=9D and some state regulator will say =E2=80=9Cwe think=C2=A0it=
=E2=80=99s actually=C2=A0because you are environmentalists,=E2=80=9D and th=
e investment manager will say =E2=80=9Cno here is our investment model that=
 considers environmental risk as a factor in assessing risk and returns,=E2=
=80=9D and the regulator will say =E2=80=9Cwe think that you are using inap=
propriately long investment horizons and imprudently weighting this risk in=
 your calculation,=E2=80=9D and the manager will provide support for its vi=
ew, and they=E2=80=99ll go back and forth. Every financial decision can als=
o become a political argument. It seems exhausting.
Elsewhere, here is an investment manager that does a lot of ESG but is  in =
trouble with European pro-ESG clients for sponsoring US anti-ESG groups:

Federated Hermes, a champion of environmentally friendly investment strateg=
ies, is coming under increasing pressure to explain its sponsorship of a co=
alition of senior US public officials which opposes action on climate chang=
e.
Three Danish pension fund clients of Federated Hermes are demanding to know=
 why it agreed to act as a gold sponsor for the State Financial Officers Fo=
undation =E2=80=94 a Republican group which has threatened to remove state =
pension assets from financial companies that do not support fossil fuel ind=
ustries. =E2=80=A6The clash highlights a tension between approaches to envi=
ronmental, social and governance standards on both sides of the Atlantic. S=
upport for stricter ESG standards across the corporate sector has been much=
 stronger among investors based in Europe than in the US where opposition t=
o action on climate change is widespread among Republican party supporters.

I guess the thinking=C2=A0is =E2=80=9Cdo ESG=C2=A0investing, but give money=
 to Republican state financial officers so they leave you alone=E2=80=9D? J=
ust exhausting.

