  [1] Or because it has the word =E2=80=9Cpreferred=E2=80=9D in the name? I=
n some investing contexts =E2=80=94 venture-capital investing in startups, =
for instance =E2=80=94 convertible preferred stock *is* better than common =
stock, because it is senior to the common stock in the capital structure; i=
f the company ends up doing poorly and selling cheaply, the preferred inves=
tors get their money back before the common investors get anything. But thi=
s preferred stock is just a common substitute, and its liquidation preferen=
ce =E2=80=94 the amount that it pays back ahead of the common =E2=80=94 is =
just $0.01 per preferred share, or $0.0001 per APE unit.=20


  [2] Here I am sort of assuming that management quality isn=E2=80=99t pric=
ed in: You have done your own research and concluded that management is wor=
se (or better) than the market thinks, etc. I think that roughly lines up w=
ith what=E2=80=99s going on in the paper.


  [3] This is of course wildly oversimplified, and different funds within t=
he same management firm will have different managers and different strategi=
es; some managers might like a company while their colleagues at other fund=
s in the same family dislike it. Still there is probably some correlation, =
some amount of shared research and committee meetings etc. that lead to an =
overall house view on many companies.


  [4] Here is   a Bloomberg News article from last year that *does* worry a=
bout the distinction, arguing (against the purists) that ESG should be more=
 like Approach 1 and less like Approach 2: =E2=80=9CLooking under the hood =
reveals that the ESG system flips the very notion of sustainable investing =
on its head. Instead of measuring the risks large companies pose to the wor=
ld, say through greenhouse gas emissions, water discharges or poor treatmen=
t of workers, ESG ratings measure the risk the world poses to the company a=
nd its bottom line.=E2=80=9D


