<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/28834876.258574/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjMvYW1jLWdvZXMtYXBlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MjQyMl9NT05FWVNU=
VUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDg=
yNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB39aa5598" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  talked yesterday</a> about AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s =
issuance of a new weird preferred stock thing called =E2=80=9CAPE units.=E2=
=80=9D At a high level, an APE unit is a slight variant on=C2=A0AMC=E2=80=
=99s=C2=A0regular common stock, and AMC=E2=80=99s issuance of one APE unit =
for each share of common stock is just a 2-for-1 stock split. That is, I th=
ink, more or less what AMC was=C2=A0<em>going for:=C2=A0</em>It wants to ha=
ve more common stock (to sell for cash, to pay employees, to pay for acquis=
itions), but it has run out of authorized common stock and can=E2=80=99t ge=
t its shareholders to approve more, so it is issuing APEs as a close substi=
tute for common. The APEs have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/28834876.258574/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci=
9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIyMDg2MTQ0L3RtMjIyMjQyMmQzX2V4My0xLmh0bQ/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5fc2ff1f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the same rights</a> as the common=
 stock: They have the same voting rights, they are entitled to any dividend=
s the common gets, they get paid the same as the common stock in a merger o=
r liquidation, etc. They represent the same economic claim on AMC=E2=80=99s=
 future cash flows as the common stock does, so in theory =E2=80=94=C2=A0th=
e theory that says that a share of stock is worth the present value of its =
expected future cash flows =E2=80=94=C2=A0they should be worth as much as t=
he common.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand the APEs aren=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0<em>actually=C2=A0</em>AMC common stock, and, uh, not everyone is=C2=A0n=
ecessarily=C2=A0buying AMC stock based on a sober analysis of its cash flow=
s. If you are investing in AMC=C2=A0for meme-driven reasons, you might pref=
er to buy the common stock because it is a more normal thing to buy and its=
 ticker (AMC) is more obviously associated with the name of the company. Or=
 you might prefer to buy the preferred stock because it is a=C2=A0<em>less=
=C2=A0</em>normal thing and that=E2=80=99s fun, or because its ticker (APE)=
 is funny.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Or, because you are a meme-stock investor, you might prefer to bu=
y=C2=A0<em>call options=C2=A0</em>on AMC, and the normal listed options ref=
erence the common stock, not the APEs, so the common should trade higher. I=
n practice, so far, the demand for regular AMC common stock is stronger tha=
n the demand for APEs; yesterday the APEs closed at $7.02 per share and the=
 common at $9.56, about a 27% discount for the APEs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a logical, finance-theoretical, cla=
ims-on-cash-flows sort of person, this might bug you. I <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28834876.258574/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjMvYW1jLWdvZXMtYXBlP2NtcGlk=
PUJCRDA4MjQyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV=
0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDgyNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cC39aa5598" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote yesterday</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might take a view like: =E2=80=
=9CAPE shares have the same economic and voting rights as AMC common shares=
, and will eventually be convertible into common shares, but they trade at =
a big discount. I should short AMC shares, buy the same number of APE share=
s, and profit when the gap closes.=E2=80=9D Good luck to you with that one!=
 I will not comment on it as a thesis except to say that AMC=E2=80=99s reta=
il shareholders seem to be endlessly angry about short sellers, so if you s=
hort AMC stock as part of an arbitrage trade they will probably be endlessl=
y angry at you.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/28834876.258574/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW52ZXN0aW5nLmNvbS9uZXdzL3N0=
b2NrLW1hcmtldC1uZXdzL2ZhbWVkLXNob3J0c2VsbGVyLWNoYW5vcy1nb2VzLWxvbmctYXBlLXN=
ob3J0LWFtYy0tY25iYy00MzJTSS0yODc4NTQw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBce4534db" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> here you go</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Speaking on CNBC's Halftime Report on Tuesday,=
 hedge fund manager and famed short-seller Jim Chanos said he has taken an =
arbitrage trade on AMC Entertainment (NYSE:AMC), buying the new APE preferr=
ed shares and shorting AMC common stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chanos said he believes they "should be the sa=
me price, or roughly the same price."</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The founder of Kynikos Associates said he is "=
counting on them to close," and he thinks "ultimately they'll all be the sa=
me class." ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"Functionally, the two securities are the same=
. And I'd guess the apes will be putting pressure on Mr. Aron, if the disco=
unt continues, to make it freely convertable sooner rather than later," Cha=
nos told CNBC.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess if you are a =E2=80=9Cfamed short-sell=
er=E2=80=9D then the AMC apes will hate you anyway, so you might as well ac=
tually do the trade?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I do want to say one other thing about this tr=
ade. The thesis here is some combination of (1) these things are economical=
ly equivalent so their prices should converge and (2) in particular, the AP=
E units will eventually=C2=A0<em>convert into=C2=A0</em>AMC shares, at whic=
h point their prices will totally converge and the trade will end automatic=
ally and profitably. Point (1) is true as a matter of economic rights, thou=
gh not necessarily as a matter of meme-stock attractiveness. Point (2) is=
=C2=A0<em>sort of=C2=A0</em>true, in that the legal terms of the APE units =
provide that they convert automatically into AMC shares as soon as AMC=E2=
=80=99s shareholders approve authorizing enough new shares to do the conver=
sion. AMC has said it has no immediate plans to seek that authorization, bu=
t Chanos argues that AMC=E2=80=99s investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0its retail =E2=
=80=9Capes=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0will put pressure on the company to do i=
t to close the APE discount, and that the board will then seek the authoriz=
ation and the shareholders will approve it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I said something in a footnote yesterday t=
hat I want to move up to the text today:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This amendment [to increase the sh=
are count and convert the APE units into common shares] <a href=3D"https://=
