<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think a few years ago a lot of financial pro=
fessionals would have said =E2=80=9Cno, that is dumb, maybe you can do that=
 with a micro-cap company, but a real public company can=E2=80=99t have a m=
ainly retail shareholder base; you need to access the big pools of wealth c=
ontrolled by institutional investors.=E2=80=9D But AMC disagrees; it <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28834876.258574/aHR0cHM6=
Ly9naXptb2RvLmNvbS9hbWMtYmVsb25ncy10by10aGUtcGVvcGxlLW5vdy0xODQ3MDIxODI3/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB32559427" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">says that</a> 80% of its stock is =
owned by retail investors, and it very consciously works on behalf of those=
 investors rather than institutions. And it works! AMC has raised tons of m=
oney by being a meme-y retail darling. Turns out, you don=E2=80=99t need in=
stitutions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still there are some kinks to work out, and vo=
ting is a big one. Here is an=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/28834876.258574/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvbS=
9jYW5uYWJpcy1hbWMtbWVtZS1zdG9ja3MtcmV0YWlsLWludmVzdG9ycy1zaGFyZWhvbGRlcnMtc=
HJveHktdm90aW5nLTIwMjEtNg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6087e4e4" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Insid=
er article from last year</a> about Tilray Brands Inc.=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cc=
annabis megamerger=E2=80=9D with Aphria Inc.:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tilray postponed a shareholder meeting to vote=
 on the deal, initially set for April 16, by two weeks. It also reduced the=
 quorum needed to vote on the proposed merger from a majority of stockholde=
rs to a third.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The delay was not due to reluctance on Tilray'=
s part, despite the recent challenges for Canadian cannabis producers, Simo=
n said in a May interview. It was a result of the makeup of Tilray's shareh=
olders, roughly 79% of which are retail investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"It's hard to get those shareholders to show u=
p and vote," Simon said. "You know, nobody has home phones anymore. No one =
answers their cellphone to an unknown number. When you mail a proxy to some=
one's house or apartment, it goes in the garbage."</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lack of participation in proxy voting has reac=
hed a tipping point recently. In July, Churchill Capital Corp. IV, which sp=
arked investor enthusiasm with its plans to acquire electric-car developer =
Lucid Motors, adjourned its special meeting because it had trouble getting =
holders of the majority of its shares to show up and vote.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The measure ended up passing with 98% approval=
, according to the company, but it took effort from executives, with Church=
ill's chair Michael Klein dialing into an investor conference call to walk =
them through the process of voting their shares online.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah, look, if you can=E2=80=99t get retail sh=
areholders to vote on a=C2=A0<em>cannabis megamerger</em>, you=E2=80=99re n=
ot going to get them to vote on authorizing new common shares to allow the =
automatic conversion of preferred equity units. If you are a meme-stock com=
pany with a retail-focused investor-relations function, you have to solve t=
he problem of voting. Though I assume that if anyone can do it,=C2=A0AMC ca=
n. Give out non-fungible tokens to shareholders who vote? Or popcorn?</p>
