<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some companies have good managers and other co=
mpanies have bad managers. If you are an investor, one thing that you can d=
o is buy stock in companies with good managers and avoid buying stock in co=
mpanies with bad managers.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> Another thing that you can do is buy stock in companies with bad manag=
ers and then run an activist campaign to replace them with good managers, r=
eaping a big profit if it works, but that is kind of an advanced move and t=
he average retail investor or even mutual fund can=E2=80=99t really do it.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A third thing that you can do is buy stock in =
companies with bad managers and then vote against management on advisory no=
nbinding shareholder proposals to register your disapproval. This is =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0distinctly third-best? You won=E2=80=99t accomplish much. US share=
holder democracy is weird: Shareholders get to vote on stuff, but their vot=
es are mostly symbolic. There is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/28834876.258574/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjcvZXh4b24tbG9zdC1hLWNsaW1hdGUtcHJveHktZmlnaHQ_Y21=
waWQ9QkJEMDgyNDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3=
NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwODI0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBde93f556" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">  some mechanism</a> that leads from =E2=80=
=9Cthe shareholders don=E2=80=99t like the managers and keep voting against=
=C2=A0them on symbolic things=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Can activist shareholder =
gets the votes to=C2=A0fire the managers and replace them with someone else=
,=E2=80=9D but it is not straightforward or quick. And for the most part it=
 would be insane to buy shares in a company you hate and just vote your sha=
res against the managers at the annual meeting. You=E2=80=99d accomplish no=
thing, and you=E2=80=99d still own shares in a company you hate.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, if you=E2=80=99re an index =
fund, that=E2=80=99s kind of the whole business. Here=E2=80=99s a fun paper=
 by Joseph Farizo, forthcoming in the Journal of Corporate Finance, titled =
=E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28834876.=
258574/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lk=
PTM1NTk3ODM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8e05219d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">(Black)Rock the Vote=
: Index Funds and Opposition to Management</a>=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I show index funds are more likely=
 to oppose management on contentious management sponsored proposals at firm=
s held only by their family=E2=80=99s index funds than on proposals at firm=
s co-held by their family=E2=80=99s active funds. Additionally, shareholder=
 proposals garner a greater level of support by index funds when the firm=
=E2=80=99s shares are not simultaneously held by a fund=E2=80=99s same-fami=
ly active funds. Consistent with =E2=80=9Clocked-in=E2=80=9D motives to mon=
itor, these results imply index funds participate as more engaged voters wh=
en same-family active funds avoid holding positions in a firm.</p></blockqu=
ote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think the intuition here is something like: =
If you run a big asset management=C2=A0firm with lots of mutual funds, ther=
e will be some companies that you like and some companies that you don=E2=
=80=99t like.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0In your actively managed funds, you will buy the companies that y=
ou like and avoid the companies that you don=E2=80=99t like. In your passiv=
ely managed index funds, you will buy the companies that you like and=C2=A0=
<em>also=C2=A0</em>the companies that you don=E2=80=99t like. But you will =
=E2=80=94 mostly=C2=A0symbolically =E2=80=94=C2=A0vote against the managers=
 at the companies you don=E2=80=99t like, because you don=E2=80=99t like th=
em.</p>
