<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are an investment manager, and you beli=
eve that climate change is real and bad and caused by fossil fuels, one thi=
ng that you might do is avoid investing in fossil-fuel companies. Here are =
two ways you might explain that choice, to yourself or your clients or anyo=
ne else who asks:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I think fossil-fuel companies are bad=
 for the world, so I do not want to fund them. This=C2=A0will raise the cos=
t of capital of fossil-fuel extraction, which will lead to less fossil-fuel=
 extraction and less climate change.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">I think that climate change is real and caused by fossil fuels, and I th=
ink that the world will increasingly realize that, and consumers and regula=
tors will respond by, for instance, taxing or banning fossil-fuel extractio=
n, or shifting away from gasoline-powered cars, or whatever. So fossil-fuel=
 companies have a lot of risk of falling demand or onerous regulation, and =
the market underprices that risk.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Those two views might lead to different invest=
ment decisions. Approach 1 might tell you to avoid investing in a big oil c=
ompany that also does a lot of innovative renewable-energy work, because yo=
u think it is morally bad, even though you think it is financially=C2=A0wel=
l positioned for a climate transition. Approach 2 might tell you to avoid i=
nvesting in a hotel company with lots of beachfront properties, because it =
is at risk from climate change, even though it did nothing wrong. But there=
 are a lot of simple overlapping cases. Pure-play thermal coal companies mi=
ght be out under either approach.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Both of these approaches can be loosely descri=
bed as =E2=80=9CESG,=E2=80=9D environmental, social and governance investin=
g. Technically they are=C2=A0 both =E2=80=9CE,=E2=80=9D but you could have =
analogous approaches for social and governance issues: Are these things=C2=
=A0<em>goals=C2=A0</em>that you want to achieve alongside your financial go=
als, or are they=C2=A0<em>risk factors=C2=A0</em>that affect your financial=
 analysis?=C2=A0Purists might say that only Approach 2 is ESG=C2=A0investin=
g, that ESG investing is about considering environmental, social and govern=
ance risks in making financial decisions, while Approach 1 is something els=
e (=E2=80=9Csocially responsible investing=E2=80=9D).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But most discussions of ESG are not done by pu=
rists, and much of the time there is no need to draw this distinction. Eith=
er approach excludes coal companies, fine. If you are a big asset manager, =
you can tell people that you are focused on ESG issues to improve returns, =
and you can tell people that you are addressing major global problems throu=
gh your ESG investing, and nobody worries much that those two things are di=
fferent.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-colo=
r: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile in US Republican Party politics ther=
e is a big anti-ESG movement now. Here, too, though, the confusion of the t=
wo ESG approaches is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0confusing. Here is <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28834876.258574/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW=
1lcy5jb20vMjAyMi8wOC8yNC9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay9kZXNhbnRpcy1mbG9yaWRhLWVzZ=
y1pbnZlc3RpbmcuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf80ebe3c" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> DealBook =
today</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gov. Ron DeSantis of Florida yesterday advance=
d his campaign against environmental, social and governance investing. The =
State Board of Administration, on which he sits, <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28834876.258574/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2JhZmxhLmNv=
bS9mc2IvUG9ydGFscy9GU0IvQ29udGVudC9UcnVzdGVlcy8yMDIyL0ZJTkFMJTIwQ29tYmluZWQ=
lMjBDYWJpbmV0JTIwTWF0ZXJpYWxzX0F1Z3VzdCUyMDIzLCUyMDIwMjIucGRm/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cBf7c4c911" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> adopted his proposal</a> to ban the consider=
ation of =E2=80=9Csocial, political or ideological interests=E2=80=9D when =
making investment decisions for the state=E2=80=99s pension fund.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CCorporate power has increasingly been=
 utilized to impose an ideological agenda on the American people through th=
e perversion of financial investment priorities under the euphemistic banne=
rs of environmental, social and corporate governance and diversity, inclusi=
on and equity,=E2=80=9D DeSantis, a Republican, <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28834876.258574/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmxnb3YuY29tL=
zIwMjIvMDgvMjMvZ292ZXJub3Itcm9uLWRlc2FudGlzLWVsaW1pbmF0ZXMtZXNnLWNvbnNpZGVy=
YXRpb25zLWZyb20tc3RhdGUtcGVuc2lvbi1pbnZlc3RtZW50cy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
